						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"> You have to deal with plenty of other limitations, like the number of sprites, colors, tiles/patterns, bankswitching, limited memory, limited vblank time, etc.</div><br /><br />That's the point I was thinking about when I read the first post. There have been many posts like this and many attempts and ideas for making the assembly language easier or bypass it altogether (some successfull) but you still have to learn about how the NES hardware works on a fairly low level to do anything worthwhile with it. You could make some kind of game maker engine, but it would likely be limited to games that were variations of the same game.</div>

